[Dr. Clement and colleagues are thanked for sending in these comments.

Dr. Clement and colleagues raise an important point about the clinical similarity (indistinguishability) of leptospirosis and Seoul hantavirus infections. Their emphasis on the need to include tests for SEOV infection in cases clinically or even laboratory diagnosed as leptospirosis is compelling. Dr. Clement has pointed out in previous comments that hantavirus infections do occur in India. He pointed out that at least 10 serologically confirmed prior cases occurred in the Mumbai region in 2016. For all these prior cases, however, including the current 11th pediatric and fatal case in Mumbai, the exact infecting hantaviral pathogen was hitherto never specified. Hantavirus infections have been reported sporadically in several states in India, including Maharashtra (see archived posts below).

Indian health authorities may wish to take advantage of Dr. Clement's offer to test samples from cases diagnosed as leptospirosis. - Mod.TY]
